From cou.: 0 Journal
From Soup: 0 Dalton Trans.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 The dynamic behaviour of the binuclear µ-hydrido µ-carbonyl cations with chelating diphosphines, [Pt2(P–P)2(µ-H)(µ-CO)]+ [P–P = dppe, 1, dppp, 2, and dppb, 3] have been investigated by multinuclear (1H, 31P and 195Pt) variable temperature NMR spectroscopy. The 195Pt and 1H results are consistent with intramolecular mutual exchange of the P atoms with respect to the bridging ligands in all of the complexes 1–3. A detailed dynamical analysis carried out on complexes 2 and 3 shows that the dynamical process exchanges the P atoms within a single diphosphino ligand, and excludes the simultaneous P atom exchange in both ligands. The bite of the diphosphino ligands affects the rate of this process in the order 3 > 2 > 1. The process follows an activation law with ΔH‡ = 67 and 60 kJ mol−1 for 2 and 3, respectively, so that P–Pt bond breaking should not be involved. The positive activation entropy (17–19 J K−1 mol−1) hints at a mechanism where the intermediate(s) have a less ordered structure than that of the stable complex. In accordance with the NMR results, two reactivity experiments provided further evidence of the intramolecular nature of the observed dynamics and exclude any equilibration path via Pt–P and/or Pt–Pt bond breaking. On these grounds, a mechanism involving rotation about a Pt–Pt bond could be proposed.
From Soup: 1 The dynamic behaviour of the binuclear µ-hydrido µ-carbonyl cations with chelating diphosphines, [Pt 2 (P–P) 2 (µ-H)(µ-CO)] + [P–P = dppe , 1 , dppp, 2 , and dppb, 3 ] have been investigated by multinuclear ( 1 H, 31 P and 195 Pt) variable temperature NMR spectroscopy . The 195 Pt and 1 H results are consistent with intramolecular mutual exchange of the P atoms with respect to the bridging ligands in all of the complexes 1–3 . A detailed dynamical analysis carried out on complexes 2 and 3 shows that the dynamical process exchanges the P atoms within a single diphosphino ligand , and excludes the simultaneous P atom exchange in both ligands . The bite of the diphosphino ligands affects the rate of this process in the order 3 > 2 > 1 . The process follows an activation law with Δ H ‡ = 67 and 60 kJ mol −1 for 2 and 3 , respectively, so that P–Pt bond breaking should not be involved. The positive activation entropy (17–19 J K −1 mol −1 ) hints at a mechanism where the intermediate(s) have a less ordered structure than that of the stable complex. In accordance with the NMR results, two reactivity experiments provided further evidence of the intramolecular nature of the observed dynamics and exclude any equilibration path via Pt–P and/or Pt–Pt bond breaking. On these grounds, a mechanism involving rotation about a Pt–Pt bond could be proposed.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Transition metal complexes comprising M–H and M–CO bonds play a fundamental role in many stoichiometric and catalytic reactions either in homogeneous and heterogeneous processes, such as hydrogenation, hydroformylation, hydrocarbon cracking and so on.1 They often undergo fluxional processes and then the dynamic behaviour of polynuclear complexes is crucial to understand the interaction of the ligands with multiple metal centres and better explain known reactions and foresee new ones.2
From Soup: 2 Transition metal complexes comprising M–H and M–CO bonds play a fundamental role in many stoichiometric and catalytic reactions either in homogeneous and heterogeneous processes, such as hydrogenation , hydroformylation , hydrocarbon cracking and so on. 1 They often undergo fluxional processes and then the dynamic behaviour of polynuclear complexes is crucial to understand the interaction of the ligands with multiple metal centres and better explain known reactions and foresee new ones. 2
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 The hydrido and carbonyl clusters probably are the most investigated compounds as models of “multimetallic activation”, and their fluxionality has been related, for example, to terminal/bridge exchange, H migration and so on.3 Binuclear species are regarded as the simplest models to understand reaction mechanisms at clusters or at metallic surfaces.4
From Soup: 3 The hydrido and carbonyl clusters probably are the most investigated compounds as models of “multimetallic activation”, and their fluxionality has been related, for example, to terminal/bridge exchange, H migration and so on. 3 Binuclear species are regarded as the simplest models to understand reaction mechanisms at clusters or at metallic surfaces. 4
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 During investigations on binuclear platinum hydrides, some of us obtained unusual platinum(I) species [Pt2(P–P)2(μ-H)(μ-CO)]+‡ with several chelating diphosphines.5 Afterwards, two homologous Pd(I) complexes with dipp6 and (S,S)-bdpp7 ligands have been reported. The only known homologue with a monodentate phosphine, namely [Pd2(PPh3)4(μ-H)(μ-CO)]+, was proposed by Zudin et al.8 as a possible intermediate in olefin insertion and in the water–gas shift reaction. The possible role of these species in reactions catalysed by organometallic Pd(II) complexes has been outlined and discussed.7,8 To elucidate their reactivity, different mono- or binuclear intermediates, originated from breaking of the Pd–Pd molecular core or from rotation around one of the bridging ligands, have been considered.
From Soup: 4 During investigations on binuclear platinum hydrides, some of us obtained unusual platinum( I ) species [Pt 2 (P–P) 2 (μ-H)(μ-CO)] + ‡ with several chelating diphosphines. 5 Afterwards, two homologous Pd( I ) complexes with dipp 6 and ( S , S )-bdpp 7 ligands have been reported. The only known homologue with a monodentate phosphine , namely [Pd 2 (PPh 3 ) 4 (μ-H)(μ-CO)] + , was proposed by Zudin et al . 8 as a possible intermediate in olefin insertion and in the water–gas shift reaction. The possible role of these species in reactions catalysed by organometallic Pd( II ) complexes has been outlined and discussed. 7,8 To elucidate their reactivity, different mono- or binuclear intermediates, originated from breaking of the Pd–Pd molecular core or from rotation around one of the bridging ligands , have been considered.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 Both Pt and Pd complexes show fluxional behaviour on the NMR time scale, namely exchange between the phosphorus atoms that averages their magnetic interactions over a wide temperature range. In the solid state, X-ray crystal structure determinations (M = Pt, P–P = dppe,5b dppcpFe,5c M = Pd, P–P = dippp6a) showed that the two metal centres are in a tetrahedrally-distorted square-planar arrangement with H and CO as bridging ligands and short M–M separations, as expected in diamagnetic d9–d9 complexes. Accordingly, M–μ-C–M angles are rather narrow (< 88°), in contrast to a description of these complexes as “metal–aldehydes”, i.e., as M(II) species.
From Soup: 5 Both Pt and Pd complexes show fluxional behaviour on the NMR time scale, namely exchange between the phosphorus atoms that averages their magnetic interactions over a wide temperature range. In the solid state, X-ray crystal structure determinations (M = Pt, P–P = dppe , 5b dppcpFe, 5c M = Pd, P–P = dippp 6a ) showed that the two metal centres are in a tetrahedrally-distorted square-planar arrangement with H and CO as bridging ligands and short M–M separations, as expected in diamagnetic d 9 –d 9 complexes. Accordingly, M–μ-C–M angles are rather narrow (< 88°), in contrast to a description of these complexes as “metal– aldehydes ”, i.e ., as M( II ) species.
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 To provide a better knowledge of the structural and dynamical properties of this class of compounds, this paper reports on an extensive investigation of the variable temperature (VT) 1H, 31P and 195Pt NMR spectra of the complexes [Pt2(P–P)2(μ-H)(μ-CO)]+ (P–P = dppe, 1; dppp, 2; dppb, 3) including a detailed dynamical line-shape analysis.
From Soup: 6 To provide a better knowledge of the structural and dynamical properties of this class of compounds, this paper reports on an extensive investigation of the variable temperature (VT) 1 H, 31 P and 195 Pt NMR spectra of the complexes [Pt 2 (P–P) 2 (μ-H)(μ-CO)] + (P–P = dppe , 1 ; dppp, 2 ; dppb, 3 ) including a detailed dynamical line-shape analysis.
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 The binuclear µ-hydrido µ-carbonyl cations with chelating diphosphines, [M2(P–P)2(µ-H)(µ-CO)]+ (M = Pd, Pt),5–8 (Scheme 1) show averaging of J-coupling to 31P at high temperature, a clear indication of exchange dynamics. Since these cations contain several magnetic nuclei, they are excellent candidates for following this process by multinuclear VT-NMR spectroscopy, in particular when M = Pt. In principle, the advantage of Pt derivatives consists in the possibility to monitor all the core nuclei (1H, 13C, 31P and 195Pt) and to get to the static situation at higher temperature, due to the known higher rigidity of Pt complexes. As a further benefit, the presence of the relative dilute 195Pt nucleus (I = 1/2; natural abundance: 33.8%) allows one to exploit the X-approximation approach9 that produces, inter alia, a definite simplification of the analysis of strongly coupled 31P NMR spectra (see below).
From Soup: 7 The binuclear µ-hydrido µ-carbonyl cations with chelating diphosphines, [M 2 (P–P) 2 (µ-H)(µ-CO)] + (M = Pd, Pt), 5–8 ( Scheme 1 ) show averaging of J -coupling to 31 P at high temperature, a clear indication of exchange dynamics. Since these cations contain several magnetic nuclei, they are excellent candidates for following this process by multinuclear VT-NMR spectroscopy , in particular when M = Pt. In principle, the advantage of Pt derivatives consists in the possibility to monitor all the core nuclei ( 1 H, 13 C, 31 P and 195 Pt) and to get to the static situation at higher temperature, due to the known higher rigidity of Pt complexes. As a further benefit, the presence of the relative dilute 195 Pt nucleus ( I = 1/2; natural abundance: 33.8%) allows one to exploit the X-approximation approach 9 that produces, inter alia , a definite simplification of the analysis of strongly coupled 31 P NMR spectra (see below).
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 In the present case, the bridging hydrido NMR results from the superposition of three sub-spectra arising from the three different isotopomeric combinations of the platinum nuclei, namely: (i) a central singlet from molecules without 195Pt nuclei (43.8%); (ii) a doublet from molecules containing one 195Pt (44 .8%); (iii) a binomial triplet from molecules having two 195Pt (11.4%). Therefore, the hydrido NMR spectrum consists of a quintet of approximate relative intensities 1 ∶ 8 ∶ 18 ∶ 8 ∶ 1 (Fig. 1(a)). The fine structure of each line of the three sub-spectra is determined by 31P couplings. At higher temperature (Fig. 1(b)), each line is split into a quintet indicating the magnetic equivalence of the four P atoms (A4Y spin system), consistent with a fast exchange process. At lower temperature (Fig. 1(c)), exchange is hindered and the molecule becomes rigid so that each line is split into a triplet of triplets consistent with coupling to two pairs of chemically equivalent 31P nuclei (AA′XX′Y spin system), namely the two Pcis (P1, P2) and the two Ptrans (P3, P4) (See Scheme 1 for numbering). The individual 1H NMR transitions within each 195Pt isotopomeric sub-spectrum can be uniquely labelled by the nuclear spin state of the four 31P nuclei. In the following, we use labels such as κλμν to denote that P1 is in spin state κ, P2 is in spin state λ, and so on. For instance, αααβ refers to the 1H NMR transition where P4 is in spin state β, whereas P1, P2 and P3 are in spin state α.
From Soup: 8 In the present case, the bridging hydrido NMR results from the superposition of three sub- spectra arising from the three different isotopomeric combinations of the platinum nuclei, namely: (i) a central singlet from molecules without 195 Pt nuclei (43.8%); (ii) a doublet from molecules containing one 195 Pt (44 .8%); (iii) a binomial triplet from molecules having two 195 Pt (11.4%). Therefore, the hydrido NMR spectrum consists of a quintet of approximate relative intensities 1 ∶ 8 ∶ 18 ∶ 8 ∶ 1 ( Fig. 1(a) ). The fine structure of each line of the three sub- spectra is determined by 31 P couplings. At higher temperature ( Fig. 1(b) ), each line is split into a quintet indicating the magnetic equivalence of the four P atoms (A 4 Y spin system), consistent with a fast exchange process. At lower temperature ( Fig. 1(c) ), exchange is hindered and the molecule becomes rigid so that each line is split into a triplet of triplets consistent with coupling to two pairs of chemically equivalent 31 P nuclei (AA′XX′Y spin system), namely the two P cis (P 1 , P 2 ) and the two P trans (P 3 , P 4 ) (See Scheme 1 for numbering). The individual 1 H NMR transitions within each 195 Pt isotopomeric sub- spectrum can be uniquely labelled by the nuclear spin state of the four 31 P nuclei. In the following, we use labels such as κλμν to denote that P 1 is in spin state κ , P 2 is in spin state λ , and so on. For instance, αααβ refers to the 1 H NMR transition where P 4 is in spin state β, whereas P 1 , P 2 and P 3 are in spin state α.
