From cou.: 9 The most relevant VT-NMR data for complexes 1–3 are summarised in Table 1 (1H) and Table 2 (31P{1H} and 195Pt{1H}).
From Soup: 9 The most relevant VT-NMR data for complexes 1–3 are summarised in Table 1 ( 1 H) and Table 2 ( 31 P{ 1 H} and 195 Pt{ 1 H}).
 ###### 
From cou.: 10 The 1H VT-NMR spectra of complexes 1–3 were acquired in normal and 31P decoupled, lH{31P}, modes in the range 183–313 K, focusing on the bridging hydrido resonance. The static lH{31P} spectra provided the hydrido chemical shift and the 195Pt connectivity (1JH–Pt) and comparison with the corresponding 1H spectra afforded the 31P connectivity (2JH–Ptrans and 2JH–Pcis). An illustrative example of this method will be given below for complex 1 (Fig. 2).
From Soup: 10 The 1 H VT-NMR spectra of complexes 1–3 were acquired in normal and 31 P decoupled, l H{ 31 P}, modes in the range 183–313 K, focusing on the bridging hydrido resonance. The static l H{ 31 P} spectra provided the hydrido chemical shift and the 195 Pt connectivity ( 1 J H–Pt ) and comparison with the corresponding 1 H spectra afforded the 31 P connectivity ( 2 J H–P trans and 2 J H–P cis ). An illustrative example of this method will be given below for complex 1 ( Fig. 2 ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 11 Table 1 summarises the 1H NMR data relative to static regime along with Tlimit, the temperature below which no further spectral modification in the hydrido region was observed. The inspection of these data indicates a close similarity between complexes 1–3 both in chemical shift and in J-coupling. The chemical shift falls in a narrow range (−1.66 to +0.83 ppm) depending on the diphosphino ligand as in the parent trihydrido complexes, [Pt2(P–P)2H3)]+.10 The low H–Pt coupling, from 450 to 484 Hz, is consistent with a hydride bridging two PtP2 moieties.11 The H–P couplings, the larger one assigned to H–Ptrans and the smaller one to H–Pcis, are in accord with a square planar coordination, according to the reported X-ray crystal structures of Pt5b,c and Pd6a derivatives. The negative sign of 2JH–Pcis is obtained from the averaged couplings measured in the fast exchange regime [ĴH–P = (2JH–Ptrans + 2JH–Pcis)/2], from the dynamical evolution of the spectra, and is also supported by theory.12 Conversely, the observed Tlimit strongly varies among 1–3 and appears related to the chemical shift difference between Pcis and Ptrans nuclei (Table 2).
From Soup: 11 Table 1 summarises the 1 H NMR data relative to static regime along with T limit , the temperature below which no further spectral modification in the hydrido region was observed. The inspection of these data indicates a close similarity between complexes 1–3 both in chemical shift and in J -coupling. The chemical shift falls in a narrow range (−1.66 to +0.83 ppm) depending on the diphosphino ligand as in the parent trihydrido complexes, [Pt 2 (P–P) 2 H 3 )] + . 10 The low H–Pt coupling, from 450 to 484 Hz, is consistent with a hydride bridging two PtP 2 moieties. 11 The H–P couplings, the larger one assigned to H–P trans and the smaller one to H–P cis , are in accord with a square planar coordination, according to the reported X-ray crystal structures of Pt 5b,c and Pd 6a derivatives. The negative sign of 2 J H–P cis is obtained from the averaged couplings measured in the fast exchange regime [ Ĵ H–P = ( 2 J H–P trans + 2 J H–P cis )/2], from the dynamical evolution of the spectra , and is also supported by theory. 12 Conversely, the observed T limit strongly varies among 1–3 and appears related to the chemical shift difference between P cis and P trans nuclei ( Table 2 ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 12 The analysis of the variable temperature 1H spectra shows further analogies among 1–3 and provides preliminary information about the dynamics. In all cases, the static-regime triplet-of-triplets pattern at low temperature translates into a motionally-narrowed quintet pattern at high temperature (see Fig. 1). In the whole temperature range explored: (i) the H–Pt couplings remain unaffected, (ii) the H–P couplings are maintained and simply averaged, (iii) transitions ββββ and αααα (cf. Fig. 1) are not broadened by the dynamic process. These results point to an intramolecular mutual exchange process.
From Soup: 12 The analysis of the variable temperature 1 H spectra shows further analogies among 1–3 and provides preliminary information about the dynamics. In all cases, the static-regime triplet-of-triplets pattern at low temperature translates into a motionally-narrowed quintet pattern at high temperature (see Fig. 1 ). In the whole temperature range explored: (i) the H–Pt couplings remain unaffected, (ii) the H–P couplings are maintained and simply averaged, (iii) transitions ββββ and αααα ( cf . Fig. 1 ) are not broadened by the dynamic process. These results point to an intramolecular mutual exchange process.
