From cou.: 14 In spite of the poor resolution, the lH VT-NMR spectra of complex 1 evidenced some features apparently peculiar in a series of strictly homologous compounds, so that complex 1 was examined in a wider temperature range (183–348 K). Unfortunately, the fast exchange limit could not be reached because the complex decomposes at T > 348 K in solution.
From Soup: 14 In spite of the poor resolution, the l H VT-NMR spectra of complex 1 evidenced some features apparently peculiar in a series of strictly homologous compounds, so that complex 1 was examined in a wider temperature range (183–348 K). Unfortunately, the fast exchange limit could not be reached because the complex decomposes at T > 348 K in solution.
 ###### 
From cou.: 15 The appearance of the 1H spectra of complexes 1–3 at 300 K suggests a quasi-static regime for 1, slow motion for 2 and a fast motional regime for 3, hence rigidity increases as 3 < 2 < 1, whereas Tlimit follows the order 2 > 3 > 1 (Table 1). This discrepancy results from the behaviour of complex 1 which has the lowest Tlimit (186 K) but displays the slower dynamics at RT.
From Soup: 15 The appearance of the 1 H spectra of complexes 1–3 at 300 K suggests a quasi-static regime for 1 , slow motion for 2 and a fast motional regime for 3 , hence rigidity increases as 3 < 2 < 1 , whereas T limit follows the order 2 > 3 > 1 ( Table 1 ). This discrepancy results from the behaviour of complex 1 which has the lowest T limit (186 K) but displays the slower dynamics at RT.
 ###### 
From cou.: 16 To facilitate the discussion, selected 1H VT-NMR spectra of complex 1 are shown in Fig. 2. Only the central sub-spectrum and the contiguous upper field satellite (δ 0.6 and −0.22, respectively, at 279 K) could be clearly observed, so that, we limit our analysis to these two sub-spectra. The assignment is unequivocally supported by the 1H{31P} spectrum (Fig. 2(a)) which shows the quintet pattern due to 195Pt coupling (relative intensities 1 ∶ 8 ∶ 18 ∶ 8 ∶ 1) and, in addition, allows one to obtain accurate Pt–H couplings. Straightforward comparison with the corresponding 1H spectrum (Fig. 2(b)) highlights the splitting of these lines due to 31P coupling. In this case, the satellite line is split into a well-resolved triplet of triplets while the central sub-spectrum appears as a broad triplet. Rather surprisingly, an opposite imprint was observed at lower temperature (Fig. 2(c)): a broader triplet and a well-resolved triplet of triplets are found for the satellite and the central sub-spectra, respectively. Considering the whole dynamical range, both sub-spectra follow the typical patterns depicted in Fig. 1. However, the central sub-spectrum reaches the static limit at 186 K and approaches the expected quintet (ĴH–P = 34 Hz) at our highest measurement temperature (348 K, 200.13 MHz, C2D2Cl4). The satellite sub-spectrum is frozen at a definitely higher temperature (283 K) and the averaged quintet cannot be perceived at 348 K. These unexpected findings seem to indicate that the central and the satellite sub-spectra are differently affected by the exchange dynamics, i.e., that the introduction of 195Pt in complex 1 differentiates the isotopomeric spin systems. However, the various isotopomers should share a common exchange mechanism and have very similar, if not identical, activation parameters since isotopic effects are expected to be small. As for the spin system itself, the data collected in Table 2 show that the major difference between 1 and 2–3 is the chemical shift difference between Pcis and Ptrans. The latter is much larger for 2 and 3 (14.1 and 10.4 ppm, respectively) than for 1 (ca. 2 ppm). However, the lH NMR spectrum is not sensitive to interactions not involving protons such as P and Pt chemical shift and Pt–P J-coupling.
