 ###### 
From cou.: 29 A further dynamic process has been observed in complex 3 at temperatures below Tlimit (228 K). The lower resolution of the slow exchange spectrum of 3 (Fig. 6) together with the additional broadening observed by further lowering the temperature, led us to presume the presence of motion at 228 K and the onset of a new process at lower temperature. The system was monitored by 31P (see ESI†) and 1H NMR from 228 to 175 K, where the solution freezes. The 31P spectra remain rather broad down to 175 K, and do not provide significant insight, apart from indicating the presence of a low activation energy process. A valuable hint was instead given by the 1H results. Even if no significant variation occurred in the hydrido region throughout the studied temperature range, at T < 209 K the apparent degeneracy of the signals due to the CH2 protons next to the P atom was raised and a splitting of these transitions observed. Besides, a similar experiment performed on complex 2 led to analogous results for T < 196 K. These findings rule out any exchange of Pcis and Ptrans, rather they hint at a slowing down of phosphine side-chain conformational motion.
From Soup: 29 A further dynamic process has been observed in complex 3 at temperatures below T limit (228 K). The lower resolution of the slow exchange spectrum of 3 ( Fig. 6 ) together with the additional broadening observed by further lowering the temperature, led us to presume the presence of motion at 228 K and the onset of a new process at lower temperature. The system was monitored by 31 P (see ESI † ) and 1 H NMR from 228 to 175 K, where the solution freezes. The 31 P spectra remain rather broad down to 175 K, and do not provide significant insight, apart from indicating the presence of a low activation energy process. A valuable hint was instead given by the 1 H results. Even if no significant variation occurred in the hydrido region throughout the studied temperature range, at T < 209 K the apparent degeneracy of the signals due to the CH 2 protons next to the P atom was raised and a splitting of these transitions observed. Besides, a similar experiment performed on complex 2 led to analogous results for T < 196 K. These findings rule out any exchange of P cis and P trans , rather they hint at a slowing down of phosphine side-chain conformational motion.
 ###### 
From cou.: 30 Although all evidences so far obtained indicate that the Pcis–Ptrans equilibration occurs via an intramolecular process, two reactivity experiments were carried out to exclude pathways involving P–Pt and/or Pt–Pt bond breaking. It is worth mentioning that Pd(I) hydrido–carbonyl cations originate from mononuclear species through acceptor–donor mechanisms6,7,14 and that, even if rather uncommon, scrambling of chelating diphosphines has been observed in mononuclear18 and binuclear19 platinum(II) hydrides.
From Soup: 30 Although all evidences so far obtained indicate that the P cis –P trans equilibration occurs via an intramolecular process, two reactivity experiments were carried out to exclude pathways involving P–Pt and/or Pt–Pt bond breaking. It is worth mentioning that Pd( I ) hydrido – carbonyl cations originate from mononuclear species through acceptor–donor mechanisms 6,7,14 and that, even if rather uncommon, scrambling of chelating diphosphines has been observed in mononuclear 18 and binuclear 19 platinum( II ) hydrides.
 ###### 
From cou.: 31 In the first experiment, performed in a NMR tube at 195 K, a stoichiometric amount of dppe ligand was added to a solution of complex 3 in CD2Cl2 and the evolution of the mixture monitored by 1H and 31P{1H} NMR spectroscopy at different temperatures and times. The resonances of complex 3 disappeared almost immediately giving rise to a complex mixture of platinum-containing species. At variance from analogous experiments carried out on the Pd derivatives,7 no resonance from hydrido complexes was observed. Hence, the binuclear hydrido carbonyl species was irreversibly disrupted and no species strictly related to the precursor of molecular core was detected.
From Soup: 31 In the first experiment, performed in a NMR tube at 195 K, a stoichiometric amount of dppe ligand was added to a solution of complex 3 in CD 2 Cl 2 and the evolution of the mixture monitored by 1 H and 31 P{ 1 H} NMR spectroscopy at different temperatures and times. The resonances of complex 3 disappeared almost immediately giving rise to a complex mixture of platinum-containing species. At variance from analogous experiments carried out on the Pd derivatives, 7 no resonance from hydrido complexes was observed. Hence, the binuclear hydrido carbonyl species was irreversibly disrupted and no species strictly related to the precursor of molecular core was detected.
 ###### 
From cou.: 32 In a further experiment, a mixture of complexes 1 and 3 in CD2Cl2 was prepared and monitored by VT-NMR spectroscopy over several days. Just after mixing, both 1 and 3 displayed the dynamic behaviour previously observed, and no reaction between the two complexes was detected. Indeed, both 1H and 31P{1H} NMR spectra of the mixture were the exact superposition of the spectra of species 1 and 3, even after long standing (20 days) in solution. Moreover a 31P 2D-NMR chemical exchange experiment (500 ms mixing time, 273 K) performed on this mixture, after 2 h standing at RT, showed the expected correlations within each complex (amenable to Pcis–Ptrans exchange) and excluded cross interaction between different species. An analogous result was obtained in a similar experiment (100 ms mixing time, 300 K) performed on this sample after 8 h standing at RT.
From Soup: 32 In a further experiment, a mixture of complexes 1 and 3 in CD 2 Cl 2 was prepared and monitored by VT-NMR spectroscopy over several days. Just after mixing , both 1 and 3 displayed the dynamic behaviour previously observed, and no reaction between the two complexes was detected. Indeed, both 1 H and 31 P{ 1 H} NMR spectra of the mixture were the exact superposition of the spectra of species 1 and 3 , even after long standing (20 days) in solution. Moreover a 31 P 2D-NMR chemical exchange experiment (500 ms mixing time, 273 K) performed on this mixture, after 2 h standing at RT, showed the expected correlations within each complex (amenable to P cis –P trans exchange) and excluded cross interaction between different species. An analogous result was obtained in a similar experiment (100 ms mixing time, 300 K) performed on this sample after 8 h standing at RT.
 ###### 
From cou.: 33 In conclusion, these reactivity experiments provide further support to intramolecular dynamics and exclude any equilibration path involving Pt–P and/or Pt–Pt bond breaking.
From Soup: 33 In conclusion, these reactivity experiments provide further support to intramolecular dynamics and exclude any equilibration path involving Pt–P and/or Pt–Pt bond breaking.
 ###### 
From cou.: 34 195Pt NMR spectroscopy confirmed the overall picture about complexes 1–3. The analysis of the spin system and of the experimental results refer to the isotopomer with a single magnetic nucleus, since the lines due to isotopomers with two 195Pt are very weak. In the static regime, the magnetic Pt nucleus is coupled, in addition to the hydrido proton, to four phosphorus atoms P3, P1, P4 and P2 (ordered on the basis of J magnitude) resulting in 16 transitions (labelled as in the ESI†) for each hydrido proton spin state. Accordingly, the 300 K spectrum of 1, in static regime, consists of an AA′XX′M spin system and displays the expected 16-line pattern, (Fig. 7). In the intermediate exchange regime, the experimental findings for complex 2 (Fig. 7) display the unaffected spectral lines with 31P nuclear spin configurations ββββ, ββαα, ααββ, αααα. This result is perfectly consistent with the mechanistic hypothesis formulated and with the coupling values of Table 2, in particular with a negative sign for 2JPt–P1. Last, the evolution of the spectral pattern to the fast exchange limit (A2X2M spin system) is expected to produce a triplet of triplets centred at δPt with a large coupling J = (1JPt–P1 + 1JPt–P3)/2 and a small one J = (2JPt–P2 + 2JPt–P4)/2 being the ββββ and αααα transitions the outside lines of the spectrum. Again, our NMR findings agree with this picture. Although none of complexes 1–3 has reached in our experimental range (193–300 K) such a fast exchange limit, the 195Pt spectrum of 3, measured at 42.8 MHz and 300 K, clearly evidences the incoming new lines between the transitions (ββββ, ββαα) and (ααββ, αααα) and a triplet emerging at the centre of the system.
From Soup: 34 195 Pt NMR spectroscopy confirmed the overall picture about complexes 1–3 . The analysis of the spin system and of the experimental results refer to the isotopomer with a single magnetic nucleus , since the lines due to isotopomers with two 195 Pt are very weak. In the static regime, the magnetic Pt nucleus is coupled, in addition to the hydrido proton , to four phosphorus atoms P 3 , P 1 , P 4 and P 2 (ordered on the basis of J magnitude) resulting in 16 transitions (labelled as in the ESI † ) for each hydrido proton spin state. Accordingly, the 300 K spectrum of 1 , in static regime, consists of an AA′XX′M spin system and displays the expected 16-line pattern, ( Fig. 7 ). In the intermediate exchange regime, the experimental findings for complex 2 ( Fig. 7 ) display the unaffected spectral lines with 31 P nuclear spin configurations ββββ, ββαα, ααββ, αααα. This result is perfectly consistent with the mechanistic hypothesis formulated and with the coupling values of Table 2 , in particular with a negative sign for 2 J Pt–P1 . Last, the evolution of the spectral pattern to the fast exchange limit (A 2 X 2 M spin system) is expected to produce a triplet of triplets centred at δ Pt with a large coupling J = ( 1 J Pt–P1 + 1 J Pt–P3 )/2 and a small one J = ( 2 J Pt–P2 + 2 J Pt–P4 )/2 being the ββββ and αααα transitions the outside lines of the spectrum . Again, our NMR findings agree with this picture. Although none of complexes 1–3 has reached in our experimental range (193–300 K) such a fast exchange limit, the 195 Pt spectrum of 3 , measured at 42.8 MHz and 300 K, clearly evidences the incoming new lines between the transitions (ββββ, ββαα) and (ααββ, αααα) and a triplet emerging at the centre of the system.
 ###### 
From cou.: 35 VT-NMR spectroscopy of all of the magnetic nuclei (1H, 31P and 195Pt) provided a detailed description of the spin system on complexes 1–3. Many spin Hamiltonian parameters have been accurately determined and the dynamical line-shape analysis revealed that the main dynamical process is the exchange of the two P nuclei belonging to a single diphosphino ligand. Accurate exchange activation parameters have been obtained. Unfortunately, NMR spectroscopy resulted to be in itself unable to give an unquestionable picture of the chemical mechanism underlying the 31P exchange dynamics of [M2(P–P)2(µ-H)(µ-CO)]+ complexes, because of the high molecular symmetry or the possible presence of intermediates elusive on the NMR time scale. Besides, the activation parameters are not in disagreement with the literature suggestions on the possible mechanisms.5b,7,14 However, some conclusions can be drawn by considering the whole of reactivity, structure, and spectroscopic data reported for these cations.
From Soup: 35 VT-NMR spectroscopy of all of the magnetic nuclei ( 1 H, 31 P and 195 Pt) provided a detailed description of the spin system on complexes 1–3 . Many spin Hamiltonian parameters have been accurately determined and the dynamical line-shape analysis revealed that the main dynamical process is the exchange of the two P nuclei belonging to a single diphosphino ligand . Accurate exchange activation parameters have been obtained. Unfortunately, NMR spectroscopy resulted to be in itself unable to give an unquestionable picture of the chemical mechanism underlying the 31 P exchange dynamics of [M 2 (P–P) 2 (µ-H)(µ-CO)] + complexes, because of the high molecular symmetry or the possible presence of intermediates elusive on the NMR time scale. Besides, the activation parameters are not in disagreement with the literature suggestions on the possible mechanisms. 5b,7,14 However, some conclusions can be drawn by considering the whole of reactivity, structure, and spectroscopic data reported for these cations .
 ###### 
From cou.: 36 The following points can be emphasized: (i) the dynamic process is intramolecular, requires low activation enthalpy (ΔH‡ = 60 ÷ 67 kJ mol−1) and shows slightly positive entropy values (ΔS‡ = 17–19 J K−1 mol−1); (ii) all compounds are diamagnetic at any temperature; (iii) the binuclear structure is unaffected in solution; (iv) both bridging ligands undergo exchange reactions, such as D/H,6b13CO/CO,7 and RNC/CO;5a,b (v) all compounds originated mononuclear species only by reaction with strong coordinating reactants;6b,8 (vi) in the vapour phase, complexes 1–3 easily lose HCO while maintaining the bimetallic structure in all of the primary decomposition pathways;20 (vii) the M–M distances established in the solid state (from 115 K to room temperature) are very short.
From Soup: 36 The following points can be emphasized: (i) the dynamic process is intramolecular, requires low activation enthalpy (Δ H ‡ = 60 ÷ 67 kJ mol −1 ) and shows slightly positive entropy values (Δ S ‡ = 17–19 J K −1 mol −1 ); (ii) all compounds are diamagnetic at any temperature; (iii) the binuclear structure is unaffected in solution; (iv) both bridging ligands undergo exchange reactions, such as D/H, 6b 13 CO/CO, 7 and RNC/CO; 5a,b (v) all compounds originated mononuclear species only by reaction with strong coordinating reactants; 6b,8 (vi) in the vapour phase, complexes 1–3 easily lose HCO while maintaining the bimetallic structure in all of the primary decomposition pathways; 20 (vii) the M–M distances established in the solid state (from 115 K to room temperature) are very short.
 ###### 
From cou.: 37 A mechanism involving the geometrical rearrangement on both metal centres was not excluded a priori,7 but was overshadowed by the observed bridge-splitting reactions (iv) that led to suggest an equilibration process via rotation around a M–X–M bond (X = CO or H) in the two equally possible mono-bridged tautomers. However, this route implicitly requires the M–M cleavage to equilibrate the four P atoms. The occurrence of bridge-splitting processes is of course out of the question, and M–M bond breaking does not seem reasonable. In fact, leaving out sophisticated explanations for the diamagnetic behaviour, points (iii)–(vii) provide compelling evidence about the strength of the M–M bond. For instance, the fragmentation pattern of cations 1–3 in the vapour phase (vi) indicates that the M–M bond is the strongest bond in the molecular core. The kinetic energy release values associated to the easy loss of HCO are lower by one order of magnitude than those calculated for the 3 H loss from the corresponding trihydrido precursors, [Pt2(P–P)2(H)3]+.20 From a different point of view, and in addition to analogous substitution products (iv), the substitution of the bridging carbonyl with a sterically demanding isocyanide in solution gave the complex [(H)(P–P)Pt–Pt(P–P)(CNR)]+ (P–P = dppe; R = (CH3)3CNC),5b4, bearing only terminal ligands, which can be considered as the effective intermediate in substitution reactions.
From Soup: 37 A mechanism involving the geometrical rearrangement on both metal centres was not excluded a priori , 7 but was overshadowed by the observed bridge-splitting reactions (iv) that led to suggest an equilibration process via rotation around a M–X–M bond (X = CO or H) in the two equally possible mono-bridged tautomers. However, this route implicitly requires the M–M cleavage to equilibrate the four P atoms. The occurrence of bridge-splitting processes is of course out of the question, and M–M bond breaking does not seem reasonable. In fact, leaving out sophisticated explanations for the diamagnetic behaviour, points (iii)–(vii) provide compelling evidence about the strength of the M–M bond. For instance, the fragmentation pattern of cations 1–3 in the vapour phase (vi) indicates that the M–M bond is the strongest bond in the molecular core. The kinetic energy release values associated to the easy loss of HCO are lower by one order of magnitude than those calculated for the 3 H loss from the corresponding trihydrido precursors, [Pt 2 (P–P) 2 (H) 3 ] + . 20 From a different point of view, and in addition to analogous substitution products (iv), the substitution of the bridging carbonyl with a sterically demanding isocyanide in solution gave the complex [(H)(P–P)Pt–Pt(P–P)(CNR)] + (P–P = dppe ; R = (CH 3 ) 3 CNC), 5b 4 , bearing only terminal ligands , which can be considered as the effective intermediate in substitution reactions.
 ###### 
From cou.: 38 All these considerations strengthen the hypothesis that the equilibration process of the cations 1–3 occurs by rotation around the M–M bond, as illustrated in Scheme 2, i.e. through a tautomer in which both H and CO ligands are terminally bonded as in the above mentioned complex 4. Indeed, easy rotation of two (P–P)Pt moieties around the Pt–Pt bond has recently been observed in the polymorphic Pt(I) hydride [Pt2(dfepe)2(H)2] in the solid state.21
From Soup: 38 All these considerations strengthen the hypothesis that the equilibration process of the cations 1–3 occurs by rotation around the M–M bond, as illustrated in Scheme 2 , i.e. through a tautomer in which both H and CO ligands are terminally bonded as in the above mentioned complex 4 . Indeed, easy rotation of two (P–P)Pt moieties around the Pt–Pt bond has recently been observed in the polymorphic Pt( I ) hydride [Pt 2 (dfepe) 2 (H) 2 ] in the solid state. 21
