From Soup: 72 The hydrido NMR spectroscopic data amenable to dynamical study are restricted to the sub-spectrum from the isotopomer with no active 195 Pt and the higher-field satellite sub- spectrum with a single 195 Pt because of extensive overlap in the other spectral regions. Each of these two series of temperature-dependent sub- spectra has been fitted to both the four- and six-site exchange models, and for each model attempts have been made to fit the spectra with reaction set II only, reaction set III only, and with both sets.
 ###### 
From cou.: 73 The hydrido NMR spectroscopic data amenable to dynamical study are restricted to the sub-spectrum from the isotopomer with no active 195Pt and the higher-field satellite sub-spectrum with a single 195Pt because of extensive overlap in the other spectral regions. Each of these two series of temperature-dependent sub-spectra has been fitted to both the four- and six-site exchange models, and for each model attempts have been made to fit the spectra with reaction set II only, reaction set III only, and with both sets.
From Soup: 73 Optimization has been carried out by Nelder–Mead Simplex method, a rather slow but very robust algorithm that relies only on the value of the target function (the sum of the squared difference between the experimental and the calculated line-shape) and does not need evaluation of the derivatives of the target function with respect to the fit parameters.
 ###### 
From cou.: 74 Optimization has been carried out by Nelder–Mead Simplex method, a rather slow but very robust algorithm that relies only on the value of the target function (the sum of the squared difference between the experimental and the calculated line-shape) and does not need evaluation of the derivatives of the target function with respect to the fit parameters.
From Soup: 74 Linear fits of the obtained exchange rate constants to the Arrhenius and Eyring equations have been carried out by the usual least-squares method.
 ###### 
From cou.: 75 Linear fits of the obtained exchange rate constants to the Arrhenius and Eyring equations have been carried out by the usual least-squares method.
